f Mach’s Positivism: Psychology, Metaphysics, Logic -- tOn the Brentanian Legacy in Twardowski’s Views on Psychology -- tDescriptive and Intentional Contents. Considerations on Husserl’s Logical Investigations from Brentano’s Empirical Point of View -- tBrentano’s Four Phases and the Rise of Scientific Philosophy in the Light of His Relation to His Students -- tBrentano in Exile: The Brentano Institute at Oxford -- tAppendix: The Idea of Philosophy as Science in Brentano -- tHabilitation Theses 1866 -- tAuguste Comte and Positive Philosophy 1869 -- tIntroduction to the Concept of the History of Philosophy -- tOn the Law of Historical Development -- tPhilosophy of the History of Philosophy -- tOn the Reasons for a Loss of Confidence in the Area of Philosophy -- tOn Schelling’s Philosophy -- tOn the Future of Philosophy -- tMy Parting Wishes for Austria 1894 -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBefore now, there has been no comprehensive analysis of the multiple relations between A. Comte’s and J.S. Mill’s positive philosophy and Franz Brentano’s work. The present volume aims to fill this gap and to identify Brentano’s position in the context of the positive philosophy of the 19th century by analyzing the following themes: the concept of positive knowledge; philosophy and empirical, genetic and descriptive psychology as sciences in Brentano, Comte and Mill; the strategies for the rebirth of philosophy in these three authors; the theory of the ascending stages of thought, of their decline, of the intentionality in Comte and Brentano; the reception of Comte’s positivism in Whewell and Mill; induction and phenomenalism in Brentano, Mill and Bain; the problem of the "I" in Hume and Brentano; mathematics as a foundational science in Brentano, Kant and Mill; Brentano’s critique of Mach’s positivism; the concept of positive science in Brentano’s metaphysics and in Husserl’s early phenomenology; the reception of Brentano’s psychology in Twardowski; The Brentano Institute at Oxford. The volume also contains the translation of the most significant writings of Brentano regarding philosophy as science. I. Tănăsescu, Romanian Academy; A. Bejinariu, Romanian Society of Phenomenology; S. Krantz Gabriel, Saint Anselm College; C. Stoenescu, University of Bucharest.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aPhilosophy, Modern. 4aPositivismus. 4aStadien des menschlichen Denkens. 4aStrategien für die Wiedergeburt der Philosophie. 4aempirische Psychologie. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aPositive philosophy.  aempirical psychology.  astages of human thought.  astrategies for the rebirth of philosophy.1 aBejinariu, Alexandru, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBejinariu, Alexandru, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBinder, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourdeau, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCapaldi, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDewalque, Arnaud, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEșanu, Andreea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGabriel, Susan Krantz, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHuemer, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIerna, Carlo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrantz Gabriel, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDonnell, Cyril, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPłotka, Witold, econtributor.4ctb4h